10:56.656 --> 10:58.658
‐ Look at all that‐‐ooh‐‐fire.

10:58.658 --> 11:00.326
‐ Ooh, kid!

11:00.326 --> 11:02.662
‐ Unlike my oil at home,
this stuff decides to go...

11:02.662 --> 11:04.414
[mimics explosion]
Right in my face.

11:04.414 --> 11:05.665
‐ That's one way to shave.

11:05.665 --> 11:07.542
[both laugh]
‐ Yeah, right?

11:07.542 --> 11:10.712
‐ It's got just a little bit
of a bend at the front

11:10.712 --> 11:13.756
<i>so I'm gonna very gently</i>
<i>bend it over.</i>

11:13.756 --> 11:15.550
<i>It straightens up</i>
<i>pretty well for me.</i>

11:15.550 --> 11:18.178
<i>It's not perfect, but I think</i>
<i>it's going to be good enough</i>

11:18.178 --> 11:20.513
and I'm fortunate to have
all my hair left.

11:20.513 --> 11:23.391
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:23.391 --> 11:25.351
‐ It's just getting late now,
for Angel.

11:25.351 --> 11:26.686
He's doing so much cleanup work

11:26.686 --> 11:28.605
without having
a quenched blade.

11:28.605 --> 11:30.023
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:30.023 --> 11:31.524
‐ Well,
Justin must have heard you

11:31.524 --> 11:33.610
because his blade
just went into the quench.

11:33.610 --> 11:36.362
He doesn't want to be
in Angel's position.

11:36.362 --> 11:38.865
<i>‐ No cracking, no warping.</i>

11:38.865 --> 11:41.993
I'm exceptionally happy
with this heat treat.

11:41.993 --> 11:43.995
<i>I'm very confident</i>
<i>that the skills I've learned</i>

11:43.995 --> 11:46.706
<i>from Theo are at least</i>
<i>the same skills</i>

11:46.706 --> 11:49.042
that he used to win,
and even though I bring

11:49.042 --> 11:51.127
my own stubbornness
to bladesmithing

11:51.127 --> 11:53.463
<i>he's put me</i>
<i>in the correct direction.</i>

11:53.463 --> 11:55.590
Yeah, we skate.

11:55.590 --> 11:57.300
‐ Angel just quenched.

11:57.300 --> 11:58.593
<i>‐ Skates right across</i>

11:58.593 --> 12:00.553
<i>and I'm just sitting here</i>
<i>just,</i>

12:00.553 --> 12:03.556
"Ahh, thank you so much."
[laughing]

12:03.556 --> 12:06.559
‐ Five, four, three,

12:06.559 --> 12:08.561
two, one.

12:08.561 --> 12:10.104
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

12:10.104 --> 12:11.272
drop your tools.

12:11.272 --> 12:13.900
This first round of competition
is over.

12:13.900 --> 12:17.028
[applause]

12:17.028 --> 12:20.073
<i>‐ With all else being equal,</i>
<i>I do think the smaller tang</i>

12:20.073 --> 12:21.908
<i>could be an issue</i>
<i>that could send me home.</i>

12:21.908 --> 12:24.827
It's in the judges hands.
We'll see what they say.

12:24.827 --> 12:27.372
‐ Bladesmiths,
that was a great first round

12:27.372 --> 12:29.415
of coal forging outdoors.

12:29.415 --> 12:30.583
Now it's time for the judges

12:30.583 --> 12:32.418
to take a closer look
at your work.

12:32.418 --> 12:33.586
Justin, you're up first.

12:33.586 --> 12:35.588
Please present your blade
to the judges.

12:35.588 --> 12:37.632
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:37.632 --> 12:39.968
<i>‐ Right now</i>
<i>the blade looks good.</i>

12:39.968 --> 12:42.971
I don't see any issues
but your handle

12:42.971 --> 12:46.307
fits perfectly in my hand.
Almost too perfect.

12:46.307 --> 12:47.892
When you're gonna
add on scales to this,

12:47.892 --> 12:50.019
it makes it even bigger,
so try to maintain

12:50.019 --> 12:53.147
the comfort it feels
in the handle.

12:53.147 --> 12:54.315
‐ Isaac, you're up next.

12:54.315 --> 12:56.109
Please present your blade
to the judges.

12:56.109 --> 12:57.777
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:57.777 --> 12:59.612
<i>‐ I like the shape</i>
<i>of this knife.</i>

12:59.612 --> 13:01.447
<i>You did a great job</i>
<i>moving the metal.</i>

13:01.447 --> 13:04.117
But there are
a couple small issues.

13:04.117 --> 13:06.953
There's some hammer marks
on the side here

13:06.953 --> 13:09.747
and the tip kinda wonks over
to one side.

13:09.747 --> 13:12.750
So it'd be nice to see
what you can do on a grinder

13:12.750 --> 13:15.003
to make it more pretty.
Nice job.

13:15.003 --> 13:17.130
‐ Thank you.

13:17.130 --> 13:18.589
‐ All right, Master Sergeant,

13:18.589 --> 13:20.717
you may present your blade
to the judges.

13:20.717 --> 13:21.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:21.968 --> 13:24.012
<i>‐ As an end user,</i>
<i>it looks good</i>

13:24.012 --> 13:26.306
with the way the form
of the blade is,

13:26.306 --> 13:28.891
but what comes into question
is this handle.

13:28.891 --> 13:31.811
It's a hidden tang,
so how you offset this

13:31.811 --> 13:33.479
is really gonna come
into question.

13:33.479 --> 13:35.523
But overall, sir, good job.

13:35.523 --> 13:37.817
‐ Thank you.

13:37.817 --> 13:39.193
‐ All right, Angel, you're up.

13:39.193 --> 13:41.070
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:41.070 --> 13:42.780
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:42.780 --> 13:44.323
<i>‐ When you started out,</i>

13:44.323 --> 13:46.492
you had a blade that was
an inch and a half wide,

13:46.492 --> 13:48.745
but only about 4 inches long.

13:48.745 --> 13:50.705
And as you drew that out
further and further,

13:50.705 --> 13:52.331
it got leaner and leaner,

13:52.331 --> 13:54.667
but my main concern is

13:54.667 --> 13:57.003
while this blade was hot,
you stuck it in the water,

13:57.003 --> 13:59.672
and that 5160
doesn't like water very much.

13:59.672 --> 14:01.674
It tends to make it
extremely brittle.

14:01.674 --> 14:05.344
There are some visible surface
cracks on here.

14:05.344 --> 14:07.138
When we see those cracks
in the metal

14:07.138 --> 14:09.098
it starts to make
some questions.

14:09.098 --> 14:10.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:10.892 --> 14:12.685
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

14:12.685 --> 14:13.978
The judges deliberation
is complete.

14:13.978 --> 14:15.730
They've made
their final decision.

14:15.730 --> 14:17.607
The bladesmith
leaving the forge is...

14:17.607 --> 14:21.069
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:21.069 --> 14:24.697
Angel, your blade
didn't make the cut.

14:24.697 --> 14:27.533
‐ Angel, it doesn't get much
tougher than a first round here

14:27.533 --> 14:29.786
when you're forging outside
with a coal forge,

14:29.786 --> 14:33.581
and you did a great job,
but with those visual cracks

14:33.581 --> 14:35.541
and in comparison
to the others,

14:35.541 --> 14:37.168
this is the leanest blade.

14:37.168 --> 14:38.711
We just don't know
how it's going to test

14:38.711 --> 14:40.588
and that's why
we're letting you go.

14:40.588 --> 14:42.715
‐ All right.

14:42.715 --> 14:45.635
‐ Angel,
please surrender your blade.

14:45.635 --> 14:49.388
<i>Really happy with</i>
<i>the kind of work I was doing,</i>

14:49.388 --> 14:51.432
just not happy with
the end result, really.

14:51.432 --> 14:54.268
<i>I don't think it showcased</i>
<i>my skills all that well,</i>

14:54.268 --> 14:56.229
but I still feel like
a winner, you know?

14:56.229 --> 14:58.106
<i>Came here,</i>
<i>did the challenge,</i>

14:58.106 --> 15:00.733
and had this once‐in‐a‐lifetime
kind of chance.

15:00.733 --> 15:03.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:03.236 --> 15:04.570
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

15:04.570 --> 15:06.405
You've made it
to the second round

15:06.405 --> 15:07.573
of this competition.

15:07.573 --> 15:09.075
Now in the first round,

15:09.075 --> 15:11.410
you guys made signature blades
in your signature style

15:11.410 --> 15:12.620
using the coal forges.

15:12.620 --> 15:14.330
Now you'll have a chance
to turn those blades

15:14.330 --> 15:16.415
into fully functional weapons
by attaching handles

15:16.415 --> 15:18.918
and guards to them
using the range of materials

15:18.918 --> 15:22.421
provided in our pantry
and underneath this cloth.

15:22.421 --> 15:26.926
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:26.926 --> 15:30.263
Gentlemen, this is
a wheelbarrow full of bricks,

15:30.263 --> 15:32.640
as you can see, and we don't
expect you to use the bricks.

15:32.640 --> 15:35.268
You just have to use
some element

15:35.268 --> 15:36.769
<i>from the wheelbarrow itself</i>

15:36.769 --> 15:38.729
<i>in your handle's construction.</i>

15:38.729 --> 15:40.106
Now remember that
after this round

15:40.106 --> 15:41.858
we'll be testing those blades

15:41.858 --> 15:43.568
<i>in a wheelbarrow</i>
<i>chop and stab</i>

15:43.568 --> 15:47.780
and for edge retention
in a construction sign slice.

15:47.780 --> 15:49.782
You'll have two hours
in which to complete your work,

15:49.782 --> 15:51.033
and at the end of this round,

15:51.033 --> 15:52.618
after your blades
have been tested,

15:52.618 --> 15:54.787
one of you will be asked
to surrender your blade

15:54.787 --> 15:56.622
and leave the forge.

15:56.622 --> 16:00.626
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your two hours starts... now.

16:00.626 --> 16:02.753
‐ Off to the races.
‐ Heavier than they look.

16:02.753 --> 16:04.422
Here's one.
‐ Yeah.

16:04.422 --> 16:06.966
‐ I like how Jon has just
brought over the Portaband

16:06.966 --> 16:09.677
still attached to the stand
to cut the handle...

16:09.677 --> 16:11.888
‐ I like it.
‐ Off of that wheelbarrow.

16:11.888 --> 16:13.139
‐ Plenty of wood
for all of 'em.

16:13.139 --> 16:14.682
‐ And it just happened in,
like, ten seconds

16:14.682 --> 16:16.309
and the handles were gone.

16:16.309 --> 16:18.811
Depending on how you design
your knife handle,

16:18.811 --> 16:20.146
you could do something like
a dagger.

16:20.146 --> 16:22.315
Sort of like a swell
on either end,

16:22.315 --> 16:24.901
and just put a piece of cheap
steel from the wheelbarrow

16:24.901 --> 16:26.485
front and back
and call it done.

16:26.485 --> 16:28.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:28.154 --> 16:30.781
<i>‐ My plan</i>
<i>to make this handle work</i>

16:30.781 --> 16:32.700
<i>for my hidden tang is</i>

16:32.700 --> 16:35.161
I'm gonna have the back end
flared out

16:35.161 --> 16:37.663
so it doesn't fly
out of your hand

16:37.663 --> 16:39.165
<i>during testing or anything,</i>

16:39.165 --> 16:40.875
<i>and then I've got to put</i>
<i>that guard on there as well</i>

16:40.875 --> 16:43.252
to keep the hand
from sliding forward.

16:43.252 --> 16:47.423
‐ Jonathan is our one smith
that has a hidden‐tang setup.

16:47.423 --> 16:49.467
It should have the easiest time
fitting a guard, yes?

16:49.467 --> 16:51.219
‐ Yeah.
‐ He just needs to dig

16:51.219 --> 16:53.054
<i>a small hole and slide</i>
<i>a guard up over there.</i>

16:53.054 --> 16:55.765
<i>Two of these knives</i>
<i>have full tangs,</i>

16:55.765 --> 16:57.391
<i>so they're gonna basically</i>
<i>have to do</i>

16:57.391 --> 16:59.518
<i>a slotted guard</i>
<i>on those two knives.</i>

16:59.518 --> 17:00.853
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:00.853 --> 17:02.521
<i>‐ I made a full‐tang knife.</i>

17:02.521 --> 17:05.816
I don't even know how to put
a guard on a full‐tang knife.

17:05.816 --> 17:08.569
Those are something you put
on hidden‐tang knives.

17:08.569 --> 17:10.780
<i>I'm gonna have</i>
<i>to figure it out.</i>

17:10.780 --> 17:12.573
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:12.573 --> 17:15.034
<i>I took two pieces</i>
<i>of the wheelbarrow handle,</i>

17:15.034 --> 17:17.912
<i>slapped a piece of dyed horn</i>
<i>in the middle.</i>

17:17.912 --> 17:19.455
<i>Glued that together.</i>

17:19.455 --> 17:22.750
<i>I'm gonna drill into it,</i>
<i>cut it in half.</i>

17:22.750 --> 17:23.751
That will be my handle scales.

17:23.751 --> 17:24.877
Oh, that's fantastic.

17:24.877 --> 17:27.380
It will add some visual beauty

17:27.380 --> 17:29.924
to what could otherwise be
a very plain handle.

17:29.924 --> 17:32.051
Beautiful.

17:32.051 --> 17:33.761
‐ The first thing I've got
to do with my tang

17:33.761 --> 17:35.471
is I've got to drill a hole
through it for the pin

17:35.471 --> 17:37.390
to be able to go through
the handle material.

17:37.390 --> 17:39.392
[whirring]

17:39.392 --> 17:40.560
‐ Mm‐hmm.

17:40.560 --> 17:41.894
<i>My tang is too hard,</i>

17:41.894 --> 17:43.813
so in order
to get this hole drilled,

17:43.813 --> 17:45.439
I have to soften that tang

17:45.439 --> 17:47.066
<i>and I don't want to lose</i>
<i>that temper in that blade,</i>

17:47.066 --> 17:48.901
<i>so I stick it</i>
<i>in a bucket full of water</i>

17:48.901 --> 17:51.737
<i>with the tang sticking out,</i>

17:51.737 --> 17:53.781
<i>and I heat up that spot</i>
<i>where I'm drilling that hole.</i>

17:53.781 --> 17:55.575
‐ Another great idea.

17:55.575 --> 17:57.410
‐ The softening
of the tang worked

17:57.410 --> 18:00.663
and drill bit's going right
through the tang like butter.

18:00.663 --> 18:02.707
Yeah, beautiful.
Yeah.

18:02.707 --> 18:06.711
‐ Bladesmiths, you have just
60 minutes remaining.

18:06.711 --> 18:10.256
‐ I see this redwood that
looks sort of cocobolo‐ish.

18:10.256 --> 18:11.757
<i>That's something</i>
<i>I'm familiar with</i>

18:11.757 --> 18:14.010
and that's what I choose
to go with for my guard.

18:14.010 --> 18:17.388
My plan for this guard
is to cut a slot in

18:17.388 --> 18:19.599
so that it fits over
the tang of my knife

18:19.599 --> 18:22.435
right above
my two handle scales.

18:22.435 --> 18:24.270
It doesn't want to go on there.

18:24.270 --> 18:26.939
I'm worried if I force it
I'm gonna split the wood.

18:26.939 --> 18:30.985
Gotta make this fit
just a little bit better.

18:30.985 --> 18:32.320
Uh...no.
Little more.

18:32.320 --> 18:34.030
<i>It's a little nerve‐racking</i>

18:34.030 --> 18:36.782
<i>and I know if I make one,</i>
<i>small mistake</i>

18:36.782 --> 18:38.951
I'll break this piece
and I won't have time

18:38.951 --> 18:40.161
<i>to make another one</i>
<i>the right way.</i>

18:40.161 --> 18:41.621
‐ Uh‐oh.
Uh‐oh.

18:41.621 --> 18:43.956
Oh, no.
‐ No, he's going to break it!

18:43.956 --> 18:46.959
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:46.959 --> 18:48.919
t
<i>to go on there</i>

18:48.919 --> 18:51.297
<i>and I know if I make</i>
<i>one, small mistake</i>

18:51.297 --> 18:53.924
I'll break this piece
and I won't have time

18:53.924 --> 18:55.134
to make another one
the right way.

18:55.134 --> 18:56.969
‐ Uh‐oh.
Uh‐oh.

18:56.969 --> 18:59.472
Oh, no.
‐ Oh, he's going to break it!

18:59.472 --> 19:00.973
‐ This needs to work.

19:00.973 --> 19:02.350
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:03.768 --> 19:04.935
All right.

19:04.935 --> 19:06.812
I finally get this guard
fitting on.

19:06.812 --> 19:09.982
<i>Now I just have to finish</i>
<i>this task the way I planned.</i>

19:09.982 --> 19:12.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:12.401 --> 19:16.072
‐ For my guard I'm choosing
stabilized, laminated,

19:16.072 --> 19:17.990
diamond wood.

19:17.990 --> 19:19.241
‐ It's going
to be interesting to see

19:19.241 --> 19:21.786
how he secures the guard
to the tang itself.

19:21.786 --> 19:23.871
Hopefully he does a little pin
or something.

19:23.871 --> 19:25.122
‐ I go to glue it up...

19:25.122 --> 19:26.332
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:26.332 --> 19:29.001
Nope.
<i>The pin won't fit,</i>

19:29.001 --> 19:30.336
and I panic.

19:30.336 --> 19:31.879
Come on...

19:31.879 --> 19:32.838
‐ It's amazing how much

19:32.838 --> 19:34.340
the pressure of this forge,

19:34.340 --> 19:36.884
your fine motor control
is compromised.

19:36.884 --> 19:38.511
‐ Got you.
Excellent.

19:38.511 --> 19:41.806
I finally get it to fit.
I'm feeling very relieved.

19:41.806 --> 19:44.684
♪ 31 minutes of beer
on the wall ♪

19:44.684 --> 19:45.976
‐ Bladesmiths,

19:45.976 --> 19:48.270
you have 30 minutes
remaining in the round!

19:48.270 --> 19:51.023
<i>‐ I'm elated that everything</i>
<i>has fit up so nice.</i>

19:51.023 --> 19:53.025
<i>The pin has seated right home.</i>

19:53.025 --> 19:54.485
I'm home free.
I'm gonna start

19:54.485 --> 19:56.987
shaping everything
and getting it all set up

19:56.987 --> 19:57.988
and looking nice and pretty.

19:57.988 --> 20:00.157
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:00.157 --> 20:02.535
Oh, I forgot to put
epoxy in it.

20:02.535 --> 20:04.537
There's nothing but a pin
holding this together.

20:04.537 --> 20:06.872
‐ He forgot to put epoxy!
‐ Well, everything's stuck now.

20:06.872 --> 20:08.499
[laughter]
‐ Yeah.

20:08.499 --> 20:10.042
‐ What I'm gonna do is
I'm gonna pop that pin

20:10.042 --> 20:11.544
out of there,

20:11.544 --> 20:14.046
pull the handle off,
fill it full of epoxy,

20:14.046 --> 20:17.049
slap it all back together
and put the pin back in.

20:17.049 --> 20:19.385
‐ My plan here is
to drill one hole

20:19.385 --> 20:21.220
all the way through
the guard and the tang

20:21.220 --> 20:23.556
<i>for a pin to fit through.</i>

20:23.556 --> 20:25.725
<i>And what do you know,</i>
<i>I can't get through</i>

20:25.725 --> 20:27.393
<i>the hardened steel</i>
<i>up near the blade.</i>

20:27.393 --> 20:29.895
I need a plan B
and I need it quick.

20:29.895 --> 20:31.522
‐ 15 minutes!

20:31.522 --> 20:32.773
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:32.773 --> 20:34.066
<i>And so what I think is,</i>

20:34.066 --> 20:35.735
<i>"Well, I can always put a pin</i>

20:35.735 --> 20:38.279
through the guard,
into the other handle scale."

20:38.279 --> 20:40.239
‐ If you're doing
a wooden guard,

20:40.239 --> 20:43.075
that would probably be
the best way to secure it.

20:43.075 --> 20:44.410
<i>‐ It's going to be</i>
<i>a vertical pin.</i>

20:44.410 --> 20:46.078
<i>Another thing</i>
<i>I wouldn't ever consider</i>

20:46.078 --> 20:47.246
<i>on a normal knife,</i>

20:47.246 --> 20:48.664
but I think it will work.

20:48.664 --> 20:49.874
It's not moving.

20:49.874 --> 20:50.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:50.916 --> 20:52.585
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths!

20:52.585 --> 20:55.212
‐ I try to clean up the handle
as much as I can.

20:55.212 --> 20:57.089
It's going to be as pretty
as I can get it

20:57.089 --> 20:59.425
in the time I've got.

20:59.425 --> 21:01.510
‐ Other than broken blades,

21:01.510 --> 21:04.597
bad handles are what send
more people home.

21:04.597 --> 21:07.892
‐ Five, four, three

21:07.892 --> 21:09.602
two, one!

21:09.602 --> 21:10.978
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

21:10.978 --> 21:12.438
drop your tools.

21:12.438 --> 21:15.065
This second round
of competition is over.

21:15.065 --> 21:18.736
‐ I could have definitely used
30 more minutes.

21:18.736 --> 21:20.946
<i>I do my best not to look</i>
<i>at the other guys</i>

21:20.946 --> 21:23.073
<i>because there's nothing</i>
<i>I can change</i>

21:23.073 --> 21:25.868
and it is what it is.

21:25.868 --> 21:29.079
‐ Bladesmiths,
this is the strength test.

21:29.079 --> 21:31.123
To test the strength
and durability of your edge

21:31.123 --> 21:33.125
as well as your construction
of your knives,

21:33.125 --> 21:34.627
I'll be bashing them
mercilessly

21:34.627 --> 21:36.295
into this wheelbarrow.
‐ [chuckling]

21:36.295 --> 21:38.130
‐ Remember,
this test is all about

21:38.130 --> 21:39.465
what that wheelbarrow
does to your knives,

21:39.465 --> 21:41.091
not what your knives do
to the wheel barrow.

21:41.091 --> 21:42.301
Jonathan, you're up first.
You ready?

21:42.301 --> 21:44.470
‐ That's what I'm here for.

21:44.470 --> 21:47.598
<i>My concern</i>
<i>with my knife is that</i>

21:47.598 --> 21:49.141
<i>with it being a hidden tang,</i>

21:49.141 --> 21:50.976
<i>there's more shock travel</i>

21:50.976 --> 21:52.978
through that tang
into the handle

21:52.978 --> 21:55.397
<i>where it could loosen up</i>
<i>the epoxy on the inside</i>

21:55.397 --> 21:58.275
and I could lose my handle
off my knife.

21:58.275 --> 22:05.366
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:14.333 --> 22:16.001
‐ Well, Jonathan,
first things first.

22:16.001 --> 22:18.254
Your blade is still
in one piece so well done.

22:18.254 --> 22:20.130
I like the fighter shape,

22:20.130 --> 22:22.341
but the edge
took some glinting here.

22:22.341 --> 22:25.052
The handle is comfortable
in my hand,

22:25.052 --> 22:28.180
but it's round up here near
the first two fingers

22:28.180 --> 22:31.183
and so it rolls in my hand
as I'm using it.

22:31.183 --> 22:32.685
But, like I said,
it is comfortable

22:32.685 --> 22:34.687
and it's a
great looking knife.

22:34.687 --> 22:36.689
So well done.
‐ Thank you.

22:36.689 --> 22:39.400
‐ Isaac, how are you feeling?
‐ Well, I'm ready.

22:39.400 --> 22:42.027
I'm‐‐I'm just hoping
my knife's ready, too.

22:42.027 --> 22:43.153
‐ Well, we'll find out.

22:43.153 --> 22:44.446
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.446 --> 22:46.365
<i>‐ This is going to be</i>
<i>a brutal test.</i>

22:46.365 --> 22:49.577
I mean, knives aren't meant
to be chopped into wheelbarrows,

22:49.577 --> 22:51.704
<i>and I know that these guys</i>
<i>really go hard</i>

22:51.704 --> 22:53.706
<i>when they test these knives</i>
<i>to really make sure</i>

22:53.706 --> 22:56.208
that only the best of the best
can survive.

22:56.208 --> 23:03.257
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:12.182 --> 23:13.183
‐ [exhales]

23:13.183 --> 23:14.518
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:14.518 --> 23:16.312
‐ Well, Isaac,
looking at the edge here,

23:16.312 --> 23:18.689
it's sharp.
I mean, the whole thing

23:18.689 --> 23:21.066
took zero damage
from the wheelbarrow.

23:21.066 --> 23:22.067
I would rather have seen

23:22.067 --> 23:23.402
something tougher
up here for the guard.

23:23.402 --> 23:25.237
Now, wood can be
kind of brittle,

23:25.237 --> 23:26.655
but the shape of your handle
is pleasant,

23:26.655 --> 23:28.782
and the finish,
although it's rough,

23:28.782 --> 23:30.409
it makes for a good grip.

23:30.409 --> 23:32.828
So all in all,
it's a good looking knife

23:32.828 --> 23:34.246
and a great edge.

23:34.246 --> 23:37.416
‐ Thank you.
‐ Justin, how you feeling?

23:37.416 --> 23:39.877
‐ Beat it up.
‐ Yes, sir.

23:39.877 --> 23:42.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:42.129 --> 23:44.381
<i>‐ It's my turn</i>
<i>and all I can think is,</i>

23:44.381 --> 23:47.760
every competition one blade
fails catastrophically.

23:47.760 --> 23:50.638
<i>The other two didn't.</i>
<i>It's going to be mine.</i>

23:50.638 --> 23:57.686
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:11.533 --> 24:13.327
‐ All right, Justin,
so first of all,

24:13.327 --> 24:14.954
of course,
it's in one piece.

24:14.954 --> 24:17.665
I didn't expect anything less,
but your edge rolled.

24:17.665 --> 24:19.625
<i>You can hear it,</i>
<i>you can see it.</i>

24:19.625 --> 24:22.461
It's no longer sharp here at
the tip and here in the middle.

24:22.461 --> 24:24.713
I like some aspects
of your handle.

24:24.713 --> 24:26.465
I like that there's
a flare at the back.

24:26.465 --> 24:28.676
It kept me in place.
I like that you did

24:28.676 --> 24:30.761
a little extra horn here
to make a‐‐

24:30.761 --> 24:33.973
a racing stripe on this thing,
but right here

24:33.973 --> 24:36.266
it's a broomstick, man,
and I had to readjust

24:36.266 --> 24:38.936
<i>a couple of times to stop it</i>
<i>from rolling in my hands.</i>

24:38.936 --> 24:44.024
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:44.024 --> 24:47.319
‐ All right, bladesmiths.
This is the sharpness test.

24:47.319 --> 24:49.238
The construction sign slice.

24:49.238 --> 24:50.823
<i>[jack hammer ringing]</i>

24:50.823 --> 24:53.659
Now, unlike the strength test,
this is all about

24:53.659 --> 24:56.662
what your weapon will do
to this sign.

24:56.662 --> 24:58.330
Jonathan, you're up first.
You ready?

24:58.330 --> 25:00.290
‐ I'm ready.
‐ Let's do this.

25:00.290 --> 25:07.297
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:19.351 --> 25:21.812
All right, Jonathan, let's
talk about your blade here.

25:21.812 --> 25:23.647
Despite having
some glinting here,

25:23.647 --> 25:25.357
the aggressive design
that you have here

25:25.357 --> 25:26.817
punctures easily and cuts.

25:26.817 --> 25:29.278
It cut through every piece
of this sign

25:29.278 --> 25:30.571
without any problems at all.

25:30.571 --> 25:33.198
Overall, sir, it will cut.

25:33.198 --> 25:34.366
‐ Thank you.

25:34.366 --> 25:35.534
‐ All right, Isaac,
it's your turn.

25:35.534 --> 25:37.327
You ready?
‐ Yes, sir.

25:37.327 --> 25:44.626
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:55.262 --> 26:02.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:03.437 --> 26:05.230
All right, Isaac,
let's talk about your blade.

26:05.230 --> 26:08.025
You might have picked up
a little chip right there.

26:08.025 --> 26:11.737
On the first simple thrust,
it got hung up a little bit

26:11.737 --> 26:14.281
but once you push it through,
it cuts.

26:14.281 --> 26:17.367
Your edge: Sharp.

26:17.367 --> 26:21.747
Easily dragging through
and cutting and stabbing.

26:21.747 --> 26:24.792
Overall, sir, your blade,
it will cut.

26:24.792 --> 26:26.752
‐ Thank you.
‐ All right, Justin.

26:26.752 --> 26:28.087
Your turn, sir.
You ready?

26:28.087 --> 26:30.130
‐ Always.
‐ Let's do this.

26:30.130 --> 26:37.179
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:50.109 --> 26:51.735
‐ [exhaling]

26:51.735 --> 26:53.946
‐ All right, Justin, let's talk
about your blade here.

26:53.946 --> 26:55.656
Your edge is sharp.

26:55.656 --> 26:57.616
It cuts easily through.

26:57.616 --> 27:01.078
Your tip punctures and
cuts cleanly all over the sign.

27:01.078 --> 27:04.623
Let's talk about that area
where the index finger goes in.

27:04.623 --> 27:06.500
It's so small right here,

27:06.500 --> 27:08.127
it can rotate
on the index finger.

27:08.127 --> 27:10.879
But overall, sir,
your blade is sharp

27:10.879 --> 27:12.965
and it will cut.

27:12.965 --> 27:14.508
‐ Thank you.

27:14.508 --> 27:18.178
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
your weapons have been tested

27:18.178 --> 27:20.180
and the judges have made
their final decision.

27:20.180 --> 27:23.308
That means it's time for one
of you to leave the forge.

27:23.308 --> 27:26.103
The bladesmith leaving
the forge is...

27:26.103 --> 27:30.649
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:30.649 --> 27:31.692
‐ All right, gentlemen.

27:31.692 --> 27:33.652
Bladesmith leaving
the forge is...

27:33.652 --> 27:37.155
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:37.155 --> 27:39.867
Justin, your blade
did not make the cut.

27:39.867 --> 27:42.119
‐ First up, Justin,
we were very pleased

27:42.119 --> 27:44.121
with all the work
that you guys turned in.

27:44.121 --> 27:47.541
Having said that, the handle
is what connects the end user

27:47.541 --> 27:49.001
to the blade.

27:49.001 --> 27:50.544
Your handle just wasn't as good

27:50.544 --> 27:52.170
as that of your competitors.

27:52.170 --> 27:55.007
For that reason,
we're sending you home.

27:55.007 --> 27:57.175
‐ Please surrender your blade.

27:57.175 --> 27:58.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:58.510 --> 28:00.178
<i>‐ It's tough leaving.</i>

28:00.178 --> 28:02.848
The fact that
the decision came down

28:02.848 --> 28:05.475
to how round my handle was,

28:05.475 --> 28:06.935
<i>it's a little heartbreaking,</i>

28:06.935 --> 28:08.729
<i>but I know what</i>
<i>to do better next time.</i>

28:08.729 --> 28:10.188
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:10.188 --> 28:11.982
‐ Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

28:11.982 --> 28:14.067
You've made it to the final
round of this competition.

28:14.067 --> 28:16.111
Now it's time to send you back
to your home forges

28:16.111 --> 28:19.823
to recreate this
iconic weapon from history.

28:19.823 --> 28:21.658
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:21.658 --> 28:23.035
The boar sword.

28:23.035 --> 28:24.369
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:24.369 --> 28:26.038
<i>Specifically designed</i>
<i>for the hunt,</i>

28:26.038 --> 28:29.541
<i>the boar sword originated</i>
<i>from 16th century Germany.</i>

28:29.541 --> 28:31.126
<i>Featuring a long,</i>
<i>reinforced blade</i>

28:31.126 --> 28:32.711
<i>with a spear‐like head,</i>

28:32.711 --> 28:34.504
<i>this weapon was built</i>
<i>to both thrust</i>

28:34.504 --> 28:36.506
<i>and withstand the power</i>
<i>of a charging boar.</i>

28:36.506 --> 28:38.050
<i>The weapon also contained</i>

28:38.050 --> 28:39.885
<i>a cross piece</i>
<i>built into the blade</i>

28:39.885 --> 28:41.762
<i>that functioned as a guard</i>
<i>to stop the animal</i>

28:41.762 --> 28:44.222
<i>from sliding down the weapon</i>
<i>and injuring the user.</i>

28:44.222 --> 28:45.891
<i>Given it's</i>
<i>highly specific nature,</i>

28:45.891 --> 28:47.559
<i>boar swords were never</i>
<i>used extensively</i>

28:47.559 --> 28:49.061
<i>by the public or by militaries</i>

28:49.061 --> 28:50.854
<i>but were</i>
<i>the favorite hunting weapon</i>

28:50.854 --> 28:52.439
<i>of the founder of the</i>
<i>Landsknecht mercenaries</i>

28:52.439 --> 28:54.566
<i>and patriarch</i>
<i>of the Habsburg Dynasty,</i>

28:54.566 --> 28:57.235
<i>16th century</i>
<i>Holy Roman Emperor,</i>

28:57.235 --> 28:58.695
<i>Maximilian.</i>

28:58.695 --> 29:00.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:00.280 --> 29:02.074
‐ You must have
a flamberge blade

29:02.074 --> 29:04.451
with four waves minimum.

29:04.451 --> 29:07.079
You must have a cross guard
and a cross bar

29:07.079 --> 29:09.915
between 5 and 6 inches
in length.

29:09.915 --> 29:11.583
<i>‐ It's a boar sword.</i>

29:11.583 --> 29:13.752
It's a sword that had
an identity crisis

29:13.752 --> 29:15.545
and now it thinks it's a spear.
[laughs]

29:15.545 --> 29:17.255
‐ You will have four days
at your home forges

29:17.255 --> 29:18.590
in which to complete
this challenge.

29:18.590 --> 29:20.300
At the end of those four days,
you'll return

29:20.300 --> 29:22.302
and present your weapons
to our panel of expert judges.

29:22.302 --> 29:24.096
And after they've tested
the hell out of them,

29:24.096 --> 29:26.473
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

29:26.473 --> 29:28.767
who leaves this forge
with a check

29:28.767 --> 29:31.269
for $10,000.

29:31.269 --> 29:34.272
Good luck.
We'll see you in four days.

29:34.272 --> 29:36.066
‐ Good job, man.

29:36.066 --> 29:39.111
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:39.111 --> 29:40.779
<i>‐ It's day one.</i>
<i>I'm back here</i>

29:40.779 --> 29:42.280
<i>in Bristol, Virginia,</i>
<i>ready to get started</i>

29:42.280 --> 29:44.241
on my boar sword.

29:44.241 --> 29:46.118
Today I really want to get
my piece of metal cut down

29:46.118 --> 29:48.620
<i>to about the size I need,</i>
<i>to about the weight I need,</i>

29:48.620 --> 29:51.331
and get this piece
forged out.

29:51.331 --> 29:53.542
I'm choosing
to go with 80CRV2.

29:53.542 --> 29:54.960
<i>It's a nice, tough steel</i>

29:54.960 --> 29:57.796
that's really good
for larger pieces.

29:57.796 --> 29:59.131
There she goes.

29:59.131 --> 30:01.800
The big challenge
is with forging this blade

30:01.800 --> 30:03.760
<i>is just</i>
<i>the sheer magnitude of it.</i>

30:03.760 --> 30:05.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:05.137 --> 30:07.723
Another big one is
the flamberge so those waves,

30:07.723 --> 30:09.307
I've never done anything
like that.

30:09.307 --> 30:10.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:10.934 --> 30:13.145
It is getting a little wonky
on me so I need to make sure

30:13.145 --> 30:14.354
I keep everything straight.

30:14.354 --> 30:16.440
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:16.440 --> 30:19.651
Got a nice,
pretty even wiggle to it now.

30:19.651 --> 30:23.113
I'm hopeful.
Things are going well thus far.

30:23.113 --> 30:27.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:27.325 --> 30:28.785
<i>‐ So it's day one.</i>

30:28.785 --> 30:30.620
<i>Excited to get to work</i>
<i>on this boar sword.</i>

30:30.620 --> 30:31.872
Ready to knock it out.

30:31.872 --> 30:33.331
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:33.331 --> 30:34.833
<i>I've never made anything</i>
<i>this big.</i>

30:34.833 --> 30:36.168
It's going to be
an interesting build.

30:36.168 --> 30:37.878
Swinging this four pound sledge

30:37.878 --> 30:39.337
is getting heavy already.

30:39.337 --> 30:40.672
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:40.672 --> 30:44.217
My game plan for today
is to get at least half

30:44.217 --> 30:46.344
<i>of the sword forged out.</i>

30:46.344 --> 30:48.388
I want to get those curves
established.

30:48.388 --> 30:51.224
<i>It's definitely interesting</i>
<i>hammering those waves in there</i>

30:51.224 --> 30:54.311
because the blade will want
to walk sideways.

30:54.311 --> 30:57.647
<i>And so having to bring it back</i>
<i>to establish that</i>

30:57.647 --> 31:00.692
<i>edge‐to‐edge straightness,</i>
<i>it's difficult.</i>

31:00.692 --> 31:02.903
I was hoping to be able to get
a little bit farther along

31:02.903 --> 31:06.490
than what I did but, uh,
I think it's going pretty well.

31:06.490 --> 31:08.033
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:08.033 --> 31:11.078
‐ Bit of a geometry dilemma
here in that

31:11.078 --> 31:13.955
I'm hitting the ceiling
before I can hit the blade

31:13.955 --> 31:15.332
on the grinder.

31:15.332 --> 31:17.501
So I'm gonna have to either

31:17.501 --> 31:20.170
take some extra wood out here
or make a cutout here.

31:20.170 --> 31:22.214
<i>I can't underestimate</i>
<i>the size of this blade.</i>

31:22.214 --> 31:24.633
<i>I gotta be really careful</i>
<i>while I'm trying to grind it</i>

31:24.633 --> 31:26.093
<i>in my tiny little shop.</i>

31:26.093 --> 31:27.844
Perfect!

31:27.844 --> 31:30.055
<i>So after cutting away a bit</i>
<i>of the table</i>

31:30.055 --> 31:32.224
and a bit of the roof,
it seems to be working now.

31:32.224 --> 31:33.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:33.892 --> 31:36.311
So just finished forging up
the cross bar,

31:36.311 --> 31:38.063
<i>so it's time to quench.</i>

31:38.063 --> 31:39.731
<i>If this goes well,</i>
<i>I'll be set up really well</i>

31:39.731 --> 31:41.066
<i>for the rest</i>
<i>of this competition.</i>

31:41.066 --> 31:43.068
<i>It goes poorly,</i>
<i>the opposite.</i>

31:43.068 --> 31:46.113
This cross bar is making it
a lot more difficult

31:46.113 --> 31:48.698
than I was anticipating
to get this whole blade hot.

31:48.698 --> 31:51.243
Fortunately,
it should be okay, still.

31:51.243 --> 31:52.786
Here we go.

31:52.786 --> 31:57.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:57.582 --> 31:59.251
That's the sound
I wanted to hear.

31:59.251 --> 32:00.293
[chuckles]

32:00.293 --> 32:01.753
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:01.753 --> 32:04.756
<i>‐ Today I hope to accomplish</i>
<i>the heat treat.</i>

32:04.756 --> 32:07.592
<i>This is the biggest thing</i>
<i>I've ever heat treated.</i>

32:07.592 --> 32:11.388
I've got a forge that I'm
borrowing from a buddy of mine.

32:11.388 --> 32:13.306
It's a five burner forge

32:13.306 --> 32:15.767
and it's normally laid down,
you know, laying perpendicular.

32:15.767 --> 32:18.603
I've got it standing up
and so this is the first time

32:18.603 --> 32:21.064
<i>I've used it in this fashion.</i>

32:21.064 --> 32:22.440
Hope it works for me.

32:22.440 --> 32:25.110
I'm gonna take my forge
and set up underneath.

32:25.110 --> 32:28.113
<i>That way I get</i>
<i>a normal heat treat</i>

32:28.113 --> 32:30.365
<i>all the way from</i>
<i>the blade tip to the tang.</i>

32:30.365 --> 32:32.617
This heat treat process
is the most critical part.

32:32.617 --> 32:35.287
If you don't have the
heat treat process down right,

32:35.287 --> 32:37.873
<i>then all you have</i>
<i>is a blade shaped object.</i>

32:37.873 --> 32:39.457
<i>You know, it's not going</i>
<i>to stay sharp,</i>

32:39.457 --> 32:41.293
<i>so I gotta</i>
<i>get this heat treat done.</i>

32:41.293 --> 32:42.627
<i>It has to happen today.</i>

32:42.627 --> 32:44.796
<i>It's go time.</i>
<i>If it doesn't go right,</i>

32:44.796 --> 32:47.299
I don't know
what I'm going to do.

32:47.299 --> 32:50.093
[hissing]

32:50.093 --> 32:53.638
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:53.638 --> 32:55.432
I do have a slight warp.

32:55.432 --> 33:01.313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:01.313 --> 33:02.480
We're good.

33:02.480 --> 33:03.940
I'm out of the woods,

33:03.940 --> 33:06.443
but still have
some work to do.

33:06.443 --> 33:08.945
‐ So I was tempering
last night with the torch

33:08.945 --> 33:11.531
and screwed the pooch
a little bit

33:11.531 --> 33:14.326
and got way too hot
on my blade,

33:14.326 --> 33:15.493
so I've lost a lot of hardness

33:15.493 --> 33:16.953
and I'm going
to have to re‐quench.

33:16.953 --> 33:19.831
Never done
a torch tempering before

33:19.831 --> 33:23.752
and I guess that's what I get
for my lack of experience.

33:23.752 --> 33:26.838
<i>A second quench</i>
<i>is just additional risk.</i>

33:26.838 --> 33:28.340
<i>Every time you quench</i>
<i>there's a risk</i>

33:28.340 --> 33:30.050
of extra warping,
of a crack,

33:30.050 --> 33:31.384
a broken blade.

33:31.384 --> 33:32.677
<i>It is quite a setback.</i>

33:32.677 --> 33:34.304
<i>If this quench fails</i>

33:34.304 --> 33:37.515
I may be forced
to start over from scratch.

33:37.515 --> 33:38.850
Here we go.

33:38.850 --> 33:41.519
<i>If this doesn't work,</i>
<i>I'm screwed.</i>

33:41.519 --> 33:47.359
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:47.359 --> 33:48.360
[blows]

33:48.360 --> 33:49.736
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:49.736 --> 33:52.906
It's definitely hard.
Disaster averted for now.

33:52.906 --> 33:54.366
So long as I can get
the tempering right

33:54.366 --> 33:56.076
on my second try.

33:56.076 --> 33:58.536
<i>This time around</i>
<i>I'm going to be really slow,</i>

33:58.536 --> 34:01.039
really careful, and I've got
my heat gun right here

34:01.039 --> 34:02.582
<i>pointing at this blade</i>
<i>the whole time.</i>

34:02.582 --> 34:04.459
<i>If it goes above 350 degrees</i>

34:04.459 --> 34:06.419
<i>I'm going to immediately</i>
<i>pull the torch</i>

34:06.419 --> 34:09.214
and make sure that I don't
over‐temper this blade again.

34:09.214 --> 34:10.382
The deed is done.

34:10.382 --> 34:12.968
This should be a strong,
hard blade now.

34:12.968 --> 34:15.220
<i>I'm gonna move forward,</i>
<i>put a handle on this,</i>

34:15.220 --> 34:17.722
polish it up,
and turn it in to the judges.

34:19.516 --> 34:20.725
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:20.725 --> 34:22.269
It's the start
of the last day.

34:22.269 --> 34:25.397
It's raining like a cow pissing
on a flat rock outside,

34:25.397 --> 34:28.066
so we're working on the handle
and the pommel,

34:28.066 --> 34:30.527
and just a little bit of cleanup
and sharpening and...

34:30.527 --> 34:32.070
[claps]
We're done.

34:32.821 --> 34:34.447
Now I'm gonna go into shaping.

34:34.447 --> 34:35.949
[whirring]

34:35.949 --> 34:37.659
That feels good and balanced
right there.

34:37.659 --> 34:39.494
<i>The farther along</i>
<i>I got on this build</i>

34:39.494 --> 34:42.455
<i>the more confident I became</i>
<i>in the weapon.</i>

34:42.455 --> 34:44.291
I didn't have enough time
to test it,

34:44.291 --> 34:46.751
but I'm confident
that it'll pass.

34:46.751 --> 34:50.297
Ladies and gentlemen,
the boar sword.

34:50.297 --> 34:56.219
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:56.219 --> 34:58.555
‐ Jon, Isaac,
welcome back to the forge.

34:58.555 --> 35:00.807
You fellas have had four days
at your home forges

35:00.807 --> 35:02.475
to work on your boar swords.

35:02.475 --> 35:04.978
Jon, tell us about your blade.

35:04.978 --> 35:06.479
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:06.479 --> 35:08.315
<i>‐ Made it out of 5160,</i>

35:08.315 --> 35:10.150
<i>the shaft is spring tempered</i>

35:10.150 --> 35:12.527
<i>whereas the blade</i>
<i>is blade tempered.</i>

35:12.527 --> 35:15.322
‐ All right, my friend.
Isaac, how'd it go for you?

35:15.322 --> 35:17.407
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:17.407 --> 35:18.992
<i>‐ The ADC rv2 that I used</i>

35:18.992 --> 35:20.744
<i>should be springy enough</i>
<i>and tough enough.</i>

35:20.744 --> 35:22.329
<i>I used mild steel</i>
<i>for all the fittings</i>

35:22.329 --> 35:24.080
<i>and I included a rain‐guard.</i>

35:24.080 --> 35:25.665
‐ All right, gentlemen,
there will be three tests.

35:25.665 --> 35:28.376
A strength test,
a sharpness test, and up first,

35:28.376 --> 35:29.961
Doug with the KEAL test.

35:29.961 --> 35:31.463
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:31.463 --> 35:32.964
All right, bladesmiths.

35:32.964 --> 35:35.550
To test the lethality
of your boar swords,

35:35.550 --> 35:38.345
I will deliver thrusts
and cuts on this boar carcass.

35:38.345 --> 35:39.929
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:39.929 --> 35:41.473
Jon, you're up first.
You ready for this.

35:41.473 --> 35:43.433
‐ Absolutely.
‐ Good luck.

35:43.433 --> 35:45.101
‐ Thanks man.

35:45.101 --> 35:48.271
<i>I can't wait to see what</i>
<i>my sword does to that boar.</i>

35:48.271 --> 35:50.607
I want to see whether or not
it will KEAL.

35:50.607 --> 35:57.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:03.620 --> 36:05.497
‐ Yeah.

36:05.497 --> 36:08.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:08.500 --> 36:11.544
‐ All right, Jon.
First off, I like the balance.

36:11.544 --> 36:13.088
I like that I can put
two hands on it,

36:13.088 --> 36:15.006
it's ovoid enough
to where I can hold on

36:15.006 --> 36:16.925
and I can tell
where the edge is.

36:16.925 --> 36:19.177
And when we're pushing
and thrusting

36:19.177 --> 36:20.553
as it's meant to be

36:20.553 --> 36:21.680
the tip is sharp enough

36:21.680 --> 36:24.432
to thrust all the way through.

36:24.432 --> 36:27.268
Your edges, as you can see,
are sharp enough

36:27.268 --> 36:30.355
to cut pieces
out of this boar carcass.

36:30.355 --> 36:32.691
Overall, sir, it will KEAL.

36:32.691 --> 36:34.442
‐ Thank you, sir.
‐ Congrats.

36:34.442 --> 36:36.236
‐ Thanks, man.

36:36.236 --> 36:38.613
‐ All right, Isaac, your turn.
Are you ready for this?

36:38.613 --> 36:40.532
‐ Let's make some bacon.

36:40.532 --> 36:43.368
<i>I think my spear is gonna do</i>
<i>really well in the KEAL test.</i>

36:43.368 --> 36:44.786
<i>It's got a good edge on it,</i>

36:44.786 --> 36:46.454
<i>it's got a good amount</i>
<i>of flex in it,</i>

36:46.454 --> 36:48.623
so it should be able to stab
right through that boar

36:48.623 --> 36:50.375
and hopefully come out again.

36:50.375 --> 36:57.215
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:59.217 --> 37:00.593
[clanging]

37:00.593 --> 37:02.679
‐ [grunting]

37:02.679 --> 37:07.600
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:07.600 --> 37:10.645
All right, Isaac.
First off, it's much lighter,

37:10.645 --> 37:12.439
so it's easier to control

37:12.439 --> 37:14.190
when you're moving
with the blade.

37:14.190 --> 37:16.943
And as you can see,
when I was thrusting in there,

37:16.943 --> 37:19.404
The point you have here
and the edges are very sharp.

37:19.404 --> 37:22.991
It thrusts all the way in,
and even when it hits bone

37:22.991 --> 37:25.952
it's got a very good flex to it
to not become bent.

37:25.952 --> 37:29.289
Overall, sir, your boar sword

37:29.289 --> 37:31.166
will make bacon and KEAL.

37:31.166 --> 37:33.084
‐ Thank you.

37:33.084 --> 37:36.755
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:36.755 --> 37:38.298
‐ [evil laughter]

37:38.298 --> 37:39.758
[both chuckle]

37:39.758 --> 37:41.509
Gentlemen, it's time
for the strength test.

37:41.509 --> 37:44.262
The sheet metal stab.

37:44.262 --> 37:45.597
Now, to test the strength

37:45.597 --> 37:46.973
and overall construction
of your blades,

37:46.973 --> 37:48.433
I'll be stabbing
into the sheet metal,

37:48.433 --> 37:49.976
<i>but this test is not about</i>

37:49.976 --> 37:51.686
what your blades do
to that target.

37:51.686 --> 37:53.938
It's about what that target
does to your blades.

37:53.938 --> 37:55.440
Jonathan, you're up first.
You ready?

37:55.440 --> 37:56.608
‐ Absolutely.

37:56.608 --> 38:03.698
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:05.283 --> 38:08.286
‐ [grunting]

38:08.286 --> 38:12.332
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:12.332 --> 38:14.667
[chuckles]

38:14.667 --> 38:18.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:18.254 --> 38:19.631
All right, Jonathan.

38:19.631 --> 38:21.591
Your blade is still sharp

38:21.591 --> 38:23.176
pretty much all the way
to the tip.

38:23.176 --> 38:25.303
Now, the tip did get flattened
a little bit.

38:25.303 --> 38:28.598
But that was a very, very acute
tip that you had on there.

38:28.598 --> 38:30.642
All in all,
it's a comfortable weapon.

38:30.642 --> 38:32.519
It certainly held up
beautifully.

38:32.519 --> 38:34.771
Nicely done.
‐ Thank you.

38:34.771 --> 38:36.815
‐ All right, Isaac.
You ready for this?

38:36.815 --> 38:38.483
‐ As ready as I'm gonna be.

38:38.483 --> 38:45.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:54.499 --> 38:59.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:59.629 --> 39:02.757
<i>‐ There's definitely</i>
<i>a significant bend.</i>

39:02.757 --> 39:05.301
<i>This could definitely</i>
<i>send me home.</i>

39:05.301 --> 39:07.679
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:07.679 --> 39:10.306
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:10.306 --> 39:12.433
[metal snapping]

39:12.433 --> 39:13.852
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:13.852 --> 39:17.480
<i>‐ There's definitely</i>
<i>a significant bend.</i>

39:17.480 --> 39:19.858
‐ All right, there's a good flex
in your blade,

39:19.858 --> 39:21.192
which we saw in an earlier test.

39:21.192 --> 39:22.902
But when you quenched
this blade,

39:22.902 --> 39:25.446
I'm assuming
right in here somewhere

39:25.446 --> 39:27.323
was where that quench stopped.

39:27.323 --> 39:31.077
So this is not really solid
right here.

39:31.077 --> 39:33.788
You did lose your tip up here

39:33.788 --> 39:36.082
but your edges held up.

39:36.082 --> 39:38.084
It's still sharp,
but you can just see

39:38.084 --> 39:40.879
there's an obvious issue
with that bend there.

39:40.879 --> 39:46.134
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:46.134 --> 39:47.677
<i>‐ As soon as Doug</i>
<i>comes forward,</i>

39:47.677 --> 39:50.221
I'm so glad
that it's gonna go through.

39:50.221 --> 39:52.348
<i>I might still have</i>
<i>a shot at this.</i>

39:52.348 --> 39:56.185
‐ All right, bladesmiths.
This is the sharpness test.

39:56.185 --> 39:58.396
To find out
if there's any sharpness left

39:58.396 --> 40:00.607
on your tip and edges,
I will take your weapon

40:00.607 --> 40:02.942
and stab and slash
at this deer hide.

40:02.942 --> 40:05.236
Now, unlike the strength test,
this is all about

40:05.236 --> 40:07.405
what your blade will do
to this deer hide.

40:07.405 --> 40:08.740
Jon, you're first.

40:08.740 --> 40:10.241
You ready for this?
‐ Let's do it.

40:10.241 --> 40:17.332
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:31.930 --> 40:34.057
‐ All right, Jon.
Looking at the tip here

40:34.057 --> 40:35.767
I can see where
it flattened out.

40:35.767 --> 40:38.645
Took a little bit of effort
to be able to puncture through,

40:38.645 --> 40:39.771
but it did.

40:39.771 --> 40:41.814
Your edges are still sharp,

40:41.814 --> 40:43.107
the cuts are clean.

40:43.107 --> 40:45.818
Overall, sir, it will cut.

40:45.818 --> 40:47.195
‐ Thank you, sir.
‐ All right, Isaac.

40:47.195 --> 40:48.488
Your turn, sir.
Are you ready?

40:48.488 --> 40:49.489
‐ I am.

40:49.489 --> 40:56.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:07.006 --> 41:08.925
‐ That's about
what I expected.

41:08.925 --> 41:11.469
‐ I straightened it.
‐ Oh, did ya?

41:11.469 --> 41:13.554
[laughter]

41:13.554 --> 41:14.847
‐ The damage to your tip

41:14.847 --> 41:16.683
on the strength test
really took it out.

41:16.683 --> 41:17.809
There is no tip to this anymore.

41:17.809 --> 41:19.352
I can put my finger on that,

41:19.352 --> 41:22.021
but the edge of your blade
on both sides,

41:22.021 --> 41:24.315
as you can see,
cut all the way through.

41:24.315 --> 41:26.025
Now the interesting thing
to note

41:26.025 --> 41:27.819
is that all that bending

41:27.819 --> 41:29.779
actually straightened
your blade.

41:29.779 --> 41:32.824
Overall, sir, it will cut.

41:32.824 --> 41:34.617
‐ Thank you.

41:34.617 --> 41:37.203
‐ Bladesmiths,
the judges have deliberated

41:37.203 --> 41:38.538
right here on the forge floor.

41:38.538 --> 41:40.873
They've made
their final decision.

41:40.873 --> 41:43.376
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:43.376 --> 41:45.962
Isaac, your blade
didn't make the cut.

41:45.962 --> 41:47.255
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:47.255 --> 41:49.382
Your blade took a bend
in the strength test

41:49.382 --> 41:51.134
and for that reason
I have to ask you

41:51.134 --> 41:53.803
to please leave the forge.

41:53.803 --> 41:55.930
‐ The end all be all of this
test was the fact

41:55.930 --> 41:57.807
that I couldn't get
a full heat treat

41:57.807 --> 41:58.933
all the way up and down
my blade,

41:58.933 --> 42:00.893
<i>and that's what sent me home.</i>

42:00.893 --> 42:02.395
<i>I made it to second place,</i>

42:02.395 --> 42:04.605
and regardless of the results
of this whole thing,

42:04.605 --> 42:06.816
it's been the best birthday
present I've ever gotten.

42:06.816 --> 42:09.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:09.444 --> 42:11.070
‐ Well, Jonathan,
it would appear

42:11.070 --> 42:13.656
the warrior ethos
runs deep in you

42:13.656 --> 42:16.117
because not only are you
an active duty marine,

42:16.117 --> 42:18.703
you are also
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

42:18.703 --> 42:22.040
That's a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

42:22.040 --> 42:23.583
Congratulations.
[applause]

42:23.583 --> 42:25.418
‐ Thank you.

42:25.418 --> 42:28.504
Being "Forged in Fire" champion,
it feels great.

42:28.504 --> 42:29.839
‐ Good job, buddy.
‐ Thank you.

42:29.839 --> 42:31.466
It's a boost of confidence.

42:31.466 --> 42:33.134
<i>It's not the big things</i>
<i>that really matter.</i>

42:33.134 --> 42:34.844
It's the little things,
the attention to detail,

42:34.844 --> 42:36.512
that make a big difference.

42:36.512 --> 42:43.352
<i>♪ ♪</i>
